(1877, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Automatic Stay Scope$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'US', $x$What is the automatic stay in a Chapter 11 case, what does it stop, and can you name a couple of important exceptions to it?$x$, $x$["Arises Automatically At Petition Filing Under Section 362", "Halts Collection Litigation Foreclosure Repossession And Setoff", "Breathing Spell To Stabilize And Negotiate A Plan", "Police And Regulatory Power Exception", "Safe Harbors For Swaps Repos Securities Contracts", "Relief From Stay Motion For Cause Or No Equity"]$x$::jsonb, $x$So the automatic stay is one of the most powerful tools in Chapter 11, and it kicks in the moment the petition is filed, automatically, under section 362. What it does is freeze almost all collection activity against the debtor. Creditors cannot start or continue lawsuits, foreclose on collateral, repossess assets, enforce liens, or exercise setoff rights. The whole point is to give the company a breathing spell so management can stabilize operations and negotiate a plan without being picked apart by individual creditors racing to grab assets. It also protects equality among creditors. But it is not absolute. A few exceptions matter. The police and regulatory power exception lets governments continue enforcement actions, like environmental or criminal proceedings. There are safe harbors for financial contracts, so counterparties to swaps, repos, and securities contracts can still close out and net. And a creditor can always move for relief from the stay for cause, or where the debtor has no equity in property that is not needed for reorganization.$x$),
(1878, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$First-Day Motions$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Walk me through the key first-day motions in a large Chapter 11, and explain what cash collateral is and why a debtor needs court authority to use it.$x$, $x$["First-Day Motions Filed At Or Near Petition To Keep Business Running", "Wages Vendors Utilities Cash Management DIP And Cash Collateral", "Cash Collateral Is Cash Subject To A Prepetition Lien", "Section 363 Bars Use Without Consent Or Court Order", "Adequate Protection Replacement Liens Or Cash Payments", "Critical Vendor And Section 503(b)(9) Considerations"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First-day motions are filed right at the petition, and the goal is keeping the lights on while everyone adjusts to bankruptcy. The classic ones are authority to pay prepetition employee wages and benefits, to honor customer programs, to pay critical vendors, to keep utilities on, to maintain the existing cash management system, and then the big financing motions, either DIP financing or use of cash collateral, often both. Cash collateral is the piece people trip on. It is cash, or cash equivalents like deposit accounts and receivables proceeds, that a secured lender has a lien on. Under section 363, the debtor cannot just spend that cash because it is the lender's collateral, so it needs either the lender's consent or a court order. To get authority over the lender's objection, the debtor must provide adequate protection, typically replacement liens on postpetition collateral, periodic cash payments, or an equity cushion, to protect the lender against any decline in value while its cash is being used to fund operations.$x$),
(1879, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Executory Contracts 365$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Under section 365, how does a debtor decide whether to assume or reject an executory contract or unexpired lease, and what happens to the counterparty in each case?$x$, $x$["Executory Means Material Performance Remaining On Both Sides", "Assume Reject Or Assume And Assign As Business Judgment", "Assumption Requires Curing Defaults And Adequate Assurance", "Rejection Is A Prepetition Breach Yielding A General Unsecured Claim", "Assumed Cure Amount Paid In Full Often Near Administrative Priority", "Timing Rules And Special 365 Caps On Lease And Employment Damages"]$x$::jsonb, $x$An executory contract is basically one where both sides still owe material performance, so a supply agreement, a lease, an IP license. Section 365 gives the debtor three options, exercised under the deferential business judgment standard: assume it, reject it, or assume and assign it to a buyer. The logic is simple economics. If the contract is favorable or essential, the debtor keeps it; if it is a money loser, it sheds it. The consequences differ sharply for the counterparty. To assume, the debtor has to cure existing defaults, compensate for losses, and give adequate assurance of future performance, so the counterparty effectively gets paid in full on its cure amount, which is a big deal. If the debtor rejects, that counts as a breach deemed to occur just before the filing, so the counterparty is left with a prepetition general unsecured claim for damages, which usually recovers cents on the dollar. There are also timing rules and special caps, for instance on real property lease and employment termination damages.$x$),
(1880, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Classes And Voting$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Explain how claims are classified in a plan of reorganization, what impairment means, and how voting works to accept the plan.$x$, $x$["Substantially Similar Claims Grouped Into Classes", "Impaired If Plan Alters Legal Equitable Or Contractual Rights", "Unimpaired Classes Deemed To Accept No Vote Needed", "Class Acceptance Needs Two-Thirds In Amount And Majority In Number", "Only Impaired Classes Vote On The Plan", "Gerrymandering Limits And At Least One Impaired Accepting Class"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When you build a plan, you sort claims and interests into classes, and the rule is that only substantially similar claims go together, so you generally cannot mix a secured lender with a trade creditor. Then each class is either impaired or unimpaired. A class is impaired if the plan alters its legal, equitable, or contractual rights in any way, even slightly. If a class is unimpaired, meaning it is left whole, it is conclusively presumed to accept and does not vote. Impaired classes are the ones that vote. For a class to accept, you need a double threshold: holders representing at least two-thirds in dollar amount and more than one-half in number of those actually voting must vote yes. Notice it is two separate tests, amount and headcount, and it is measured against votes cast, not the whole class. There are limits on gerrymandering classes to manufacture a yes vote, and crucially, to confirm you need at least one impaired class to accept, excluding insiders, which becomes the gateway to cramdown.$x$),
(1881, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Section 1129 Confirmation$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$What are the main requirements a plan must satisfy under section 1129 to be confirmed, assuming every impaired class has voted to accept?$x$, $x$["Good Faith And Proper Classification And Disclosure", "Best-Interests Test For Each Impaired Dissenting Holder", "Feasibility No Liquidation Or Further Reorganization Needed", "Administrative And Priority Claims Paid In Full Or As Allowed", "At Least One Impaired Class Accepts Excluding Insiders", "Fee And Regulatory Compliance Plus Retiree Benefit Continuation"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Even with a fully consensual plan where every impaired class votes yes, section 1129(a) still has a checklist the court applies, because confirmation protects dissenting individuals and the integrity of the process, not just majorities. The big ones I focus on are: the plan complies with the Code and was proposed in good faith and not by forbidden means; proper disclosure was made. Then the best-interests test, which protects any single dissenting holder by guaranteeing they get at least liquidation value. Feasibility is huge, the court must find confirmation is not likely to be followed by liquidation or the need for further restructuring, so the projections have to hold up. Administrative and priority claims generally must be paid in full, in cash, unless the holder agrees otherwise. At least one impaired class must have accepted, excluding insiders. And there are cleanup items, all statutory fees paid, retiree benefits continued, and any required regulatory approvals obtained. Hit all of those and the plan confirms consensually.$x$),
(1882, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Cross-Class Cramdown$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A senior secured class accepts the plan but the unsecured class rejects it. How can the debtor still confirm through cramdown, and how is the cramdown interest rate on the secured claim set?$x$, $x$["Cramdown Under Section 1129(b) Over A Dissenting Class", "Needs One Accepting Impaired Class Plus All Other 1129(a) Tests", "Fair And Equitable Plus No Unfair Discrimination", "Absolute Priority Rule Blocks Junior Recovery Over Objection", "Secured Cramdown Defer Payments Of Present Value Of Claim", "Till Formula Prime Plus Risk Adjustment For The Rate"]$x$::jsonb, $x$If at least one impaired class accepts, the debtor can still confirm over the dissenting unsecured class using cramdown under section 1129(b). Two extra standards apply on top of all the regular 1129(a) requirements: the plan cannot unfairly discriminate against the rejecting class, and it must be fair and equitable to it. For unsecured creditors, fair and equitable means the absolute priority rule, so a junior class, typically equity, cannot keep or receive anything on account of its old interest unless the dissenting senior class is paid in full, subject to the new value exception. For the secured class, if you are cramming that down instead, fair and equitable lets the debtor keep the lien and stretch out payments, but those deferred payments must have a present value at least equal to the secured claim. That is where the rate matters. Courts commonly use the Till formula approach: start from the national prime rate as the base and add a risk premium reflecting the debtor's circumstances, the collateral, and plan duration, so the stream of payments discounts back to the full value of the claim.$x$),
(1883, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Best-Interests Test$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Explain the best-interests-of-creditors test and how a liquidation analysis is built to satisfy it.$x$, $x$["Each Impaired Dissenting Holder Gets At Least Chapter 7 Value", "Applies Per Individual Holder Not Per Class", "Hypothetical Chapter 7 Liquidation On The Effective Date", "Gross Asset Recoveries At Distressed Values By Category", "Subtract Trustee Fees Wind-Down Costs And Administrative Claims", "Waterfall By Priority To Derive Recovery Percentages"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The best-interests test, in section 1129(a)(7), is a floor that protects dissenters. It says any impaired holder who votes no must receive under the plan at least as much as they would get if the company were liquidated under Chapter 7 instead. Importantly it is tested holder by holder, not class by class, so even one objector triggers it. To prove it, you build a liquidation analysis. You start with the balance sheet and estimate what each asset category would actually fetch in a forced Chapter 7 sale as of the effective date, applying recovery percentages, receivables higher, specialized inventory and goodwill much lower. That gives you gross proceeds. Then you subtract the costs of liquidation, a Chapter 7 trustee's fees and commission, wind-down and professional costs, and any incremental administrative and priority claims. What is left flows down the absolute priority waterfall, secured first from their collateral, then admin and priority, then unsecured. The resulting recovery for each class is the hypothetical Chapter 7 number, and the plan must beat or match it for every dissenting holder.$x$),
(1884, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$KEIP Versus KERP$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$What is the difference between a KEIP and a KERP in Chapter 11, and why is that distinction legally important for getting one approved for senior executives?$x$, $x$["KEIP Is Incentive-Based KERP Is Retention-Based", "Section 503(c) Restricts Insider Retention And Severance Pay", "KERP To Insiders Faces Strict 503(c)(1) Requirements", "Incentive Plans Reviewed Under Business Judgment If Truly Incentivizing", "Metrics Must Be Demanding Not Lay-Ups To Avoid Disguised Retention", "Court And UST Scrutiny Of Insider Status And Benchmarks"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A KEIP is a key employee incentive plan and a KERP is a key employee retention plan, and the difference is exactly what the names say. A KERP pays people to stay, a flat retention bonus for not quitting. A KEIP pays people to hit performance targets, like an asset-sale price, an EBITDA threshold, or emergence by a date. That distinction is legally critical because of section 503(c), which Congress added specifically to stop the old practice of showering insiders with retention bonuses on the way into bankruptcy. For insiders, retention and severance payments face very strict statutory hurdles under 503(c)(1) that are hard to meet, so a pure stay bonus to a senior executive usually fails. Incentive plans fall outside that straitjacket and are judged under the ordinary business judgment standard, provided they are genuinely incentivizing. So the fight is almost always whether the metrics are real stretch goals or just lay-ups the executives will clear no matter what, in which case courts and the US Trustee will call it a disguised KERP and reject it.$x$),
(1885, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Restructuring Support Agreement$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What is a restructuring support agreement, and why would a company and its key creditors sign one before filing for Chapter 11?$x$, $x$["RSA Is Lock-Up Contract To Support A Deal", "Binds Signatories To Vote For The Plan", "Provides Pre-Filing Certainty And Speed", "Milestones, Fiduciary Out, Termination Events", "Reduces Execution Risk And Professional Fees", "Often Paired With Backstop Or Equity Commitment"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A restructuring support agreement, or RSA, is essentially a lock-up contract between the company and its major creditors where everyone agrees in advance to support a specific restructuring deal. Each signatory commits to vote for the plan, not to flip sides, and often not to trade their claims unless the buyer also signs on. The point is certainty and speed. Instead of filing blind and fighting it out in court, you walk in with a deal already papered, which lets you run a pre-packaged or pre-negotiated case in weeks rather than a year. That cuts professional fees, reduces business disruption, and signals to vendors and customers that there is a path out. RSAs include milestones the company must hit, like filing a plan by a certain date, plus termination events if those slip. There is usually a fiduciary out so the board can pivot to a better proposal. They are frequently paired with a backstop or equity commitment, so the capital is lined up too. The risk is locking in terms too early if the business deteriorates.$x$),
(1886, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Ad Hoc Group Vs UCC$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'US', $x$Walk me through the difference between an ad hoc creditor group and an official creditors committee in a Chapter 11 case.$x$, $x$["Ad Hoc Group Is Self-Organized, Self-Funded Subset", "UCC Is Appointed By US Trustee", "UCC Owes Fiduciary Duty To All Unsecureds", "UCC Professional Fees Paid By The Estate", "Ad Hoc Often Single Class Or Single Tranche", "Disclosure And Rule 2019 Holdings Reporting", "Different Leverage And Standing In The Case"]$x$::jsonb, $x$An ad hoc group is a self-organized cluster of creditors, usually holding the same tranche, who band together to negotiate with more leverage and share legal and advisory costs. They represent only their own economic interest, so they can be aggressive and tactical. An official committee, by contrast, is appointed by the US Trustee, typically the unsecured creditors committee, and it owes a fiduciary duty to all unsecured creditors as a class, not just its members. That is a big distinction. The committee acts as a watchdog over the debtor, can investigate the estate, challenge liens, and its professional fees are paid by the estate, whereas an ad hoc group generally funds itself unless it negotiates a fee reimbursement into the deal. Membership also differs. The committee is a cross-section appointed early; an ad hoc group is whoever chooses to join. Both have to think about disclosure, and ad hoc groups file Rule 2019 statements revealing holdings. In practice the committee gives broad standing and information rights, while the ad hoc group gives concentrated negotiating power.$x$),
(1887, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Priming And Intercreditor$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A distressed borrower wants to raise new money but its existing first-lien lenders have a lien on substantially all assets. How can a priming fight play out, and what role does the intercreditor agreement and the credit agreement play?$x$, $x$["Priming Lien Jumps Ahead Of Existing Secured Debt", "Consensual Or Nonconsensual Priming Under 364(d)", "Adequate Protection For Primed Lenders", "Credit Agreement Sacred Rights And Required Lender Votes", "Intercreditor And Pari Subordination Mechanics", "Open Versus Closed Documents And Uptier Capacity", "Litigation Risk And Serta/Mitel Style Disputes"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A priming fight is about whether new money can leapfrog the existing first lien. There are two routes. Consensual priming happens when enough existing lenders agree, often because the new money is structured as an uptier where participating lenders roll up into a new super-senior tranche ahead of holdouts. Nonconsensual priming runs through section 364(d) in bankruptcy, where the court can authorize a priming DIP only if the primed lenders get adequate protection, meaning their collateral cushion is genuinely safe. The documents drive everything. The credit agreement defines sacred rights and the vote threshold needed, whether required lenders, a simple majority, can amend the waterfall, or whether each affected lender must consent. If the document is loose, a majority can prime the minority, which is exactly the uptier playbook. The intercreditor agreement governs lien priority and turnover between tranches. These deals are heavily litigated, as Serta and Mitel showed, because holdouts argue open-market or pro-rata provisions were breached. So it is a contract-reading exercise layered on top of leverage.$x$),
(1888, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Credit Bidding Mechanics$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$Explain credit bidding in a 363 sale. Why is it powerful for a secured lender, and when can a court limit it?$x$, $x$["Bid Debt Instead Of Cash Up To Claim Amount", "Section 363(k) Right For Secured Creditors", "No Fresh Cash Needed, Sets Effective Floor", "Loan-To-Own And Fulcrum Strategy", "Court Can Limit For Cause Per RadLAX", "Disputed Lien Or Inequitable Conduct Limits It", "Chills Or Anchors Third-Party Bidding"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Credit bidding lets a secured creditor bid its debt rather than cash to buy the collateral in a 363 sale, up to the full face amount of its allowed claim. It comes from section 363(k). The power is obvious. The lender does not need to write a new check; it just offsets the purchase price against what it is already owed, so it can outbid cash buyers and effectively set a floor under the asset. This is the heart of a loan-to-own strategy, where a distressed investor buys the fulcrum debt cheap and then credit bids to take the company. It also protects the lender from a fire sale, since it can always step in rather than watch collateral go for less than its claim. But it is not absolute. Under the RadLAX line and section 363(k), a court can limit or deny credit bidding for cause. Typical causes are a genuinely disputed or unperfected lien, inequitable conduct by the lender, or where allowing it would chill the auction and depress value for the estate. So courts balance the lender right against maximizing recovery for everyone.$x$),
(1889, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Make-Whole And No-Call$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$Bondholders are arguing they are owed a make-whole premium when a company repays debt early in bankruptcy. What is the make-whole, what is a no-call, and why do these disputes arise in restructurings?$x$, $x$["Make-Whole Compensates For Lost Future Interest", "No-Call Bars Prepayment For A Period", "Acceleration On Filing May Negate Make-Whole", "Indenture Language Determines Entitlement", "Unmatured Interest Disallowance Under 502(b)(2)", "Solvent Debtor Exception Debate", "Circuit Split, Ultra Petroleum And Hertz"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A make-whole is a contractual premium that compensates a lender for early repayment, roughly the present value of the interest they would have earned through maturity, so the lender is made whole for the lost yield. A no-call is a related provision that simply forbids prepayment at all for a set period. These fights blow up in restructurings because a bankruptcy filing usually triggers automatic acceleration of the debt. Once the debt is accelerated and due now, the company argues there is no early repayment, so no make-whole is owed, while creditors argue the premium or damages for breaking the no-call survive anyway. It all turns on the precise indenture language, whether it expressly says the premium is due upon acceleration or bankruptcy. There is also a Code overlay, because make-wholes can look like unmatured interest, which section 502(b)(2) disallows. The hot issue is the solvent-debtor exception, where if the company is solvent courts have been more willing to enforce the premium. The case law splits, with Ultra Petroleum and Hertz pulling different ways, so outcomes are very document and circuit specific.$x$),
(1890, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Equitable Subordination$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$Distinguish equitable subordination from recharacterization. When might a court use each against an insider lender, and what is the practical effect on recoveries?$x$, $x$["Equitable Subordination Punishes Inequitable Conduct", "Keeps Claim As Debt But Drops Priority", "Recharacterization Treats Loan As Equity", "Recharacterization Looks At Substance Of Advance", "Insider And Affiliate Lending Triggers Scrutiny", "Section 510(c) Versus Judicial Doctrine", "Effect: Subordinated Or Wiped To Equity"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These two doctrines both knock an insider lender down the waterfall, but they work differently. Equitable subordination, under section 510(c), is about misconduct. The claim is a valid debt, but the insider did something inequitable, like using control to harm other creditors, undercapitalizing the company, or self-dealing, so the court subordinates that claim below other creditors of the same rank as a remedy. The claim still exists as debt; it just gets paid after everyone the insider harmed. Recharacterization is different in kind. The court asks whether the advance was really debt at all or whether, in substance, it was an equity contribution dressed up as a loan. Factors include whether there was a fixed maturity, a real interest rate, repayment expectations, and whether an outside lender would ever have made the loan. If it is recharacterized, it stops being a claim and becomes equity, which in most insolvent cases means it recovers essentially nothing. So the practical difference is severity. Subordination reorders you; recharacterization can wipe you out entirely by pushing you behind all creditors into the equity tier.$x$),
(1891, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Fraudulent Transfer LBO$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A company that did a leveraged buyout three years ago is now insolvent. How could a fraudulent conveyance claim arise from that LBO, and who would bring it and against whom?$x$, $x$["Constructive Versus Actual Fraud", "Reasonably Equivalent Value And Insolvency Test", "LBO Debt Burdens Company, Cash Goes To Sellers", "Look-Back Period Under 548 And State UVTA", "Claim Brought By Trustee Or Committee", "Targets Selling Shareholders And Sponsor", "Section 546(e) Safe Harbor Defense"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A fraudulent conveyance claim attacks the LBO itself as a transfer that hurt creditors. The theory is usually constructive fraud, not intent to defraud. In an LBO the company takes on a pile of new debt, and that cash flows out to the selling shareholders who cash out their equity. The company is left burdened with the debt but, the argument goes, did not receive reasonably equivalent value in return, and if it was insolvent at the time or rendered insolvent by the deal, the transfers can be unwound. So you test two things, reasonably equivalent value and insolvency or unreasonably small capital at closing. The claim is typically brought by the trustee or the creditors committee, standing in for creditors, and the targets are whoever got the money, the selling shareholders and sometimes the sponsor and advisors. The look-back is two years under section 548 but often longer using state law, the UVTA, which the trustee can borrow. The big defense is the section 546(e) securities safe harbor, which has shielded many LBO payments routed through financial intermediaries, so these claims are strong in theory but contested in practice.$x$),
(1892, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Claims Trading Angle$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$From a distressed-debt investor's perspective, why buy a claim or a tranche of bank debt in a restructuring, and what are the main risks of trading into a position?$x$, $x$["Buy Below Par To Capture Recovery Upside", "Target Fulcrum For Equity Conversion And Control", "Build Blocking Position To Influence Plan", "Risks: Claim Disallowance, Subordination, Setoff", "Trade Documentation And Successor Liability", "Restricted Versus Public Side, MNPI", "Liquidity, Settlement Delay, RSA Lock-Ups"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A distressed investor buys a claim because the market price sits well below where they think the eventual recovery lands, so it is a mispriced security with a catalyst, the restructuring itself. The most strategic play is buying the fulcrum, the tranche that converts to equity, because that is where you get loan-to-own control of the reorganized company. Even short of the fulcrum, buying enough of a class lets you build a blocking position, since you can hold up a plan that needs your class vote, which gives leverage to improve terms. The risks are real. The claim might be disallowed, reduced, subordinated, or hit by a setoff or a preference, and crucially when you buy a claim you generally take it subject to those defenses, so you inherit the seller's baggage. Documentation matters, including representations on what you are buying and successor-liability concerns. There is also the wall, where holding material nonpublic information can restrict trading, so you choose to be public or private side. And liquidity is thin, settlement is slow, and an RSA may lock up the claim, limiting your exit.$x$),
(1893, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Prepack Versus Freefall$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'US', $x$Walk me through the difference between a pre-packaged, a pre-arranged, and a free-fall Chapter 11, and what each one is trying to optimize for.$x$, $x$["Prepack: votes solicited pre-filing, plan ready on day one", "Pre-arranged: RSA / deal with key creditors but votes solicited in court", "Free-fall: file first, negotiate plan inside bankruptcy", "Trade-off is speed and cost versus flexibility and inclusiveness", "Prepack minimizes time in court, business disruption, professional fees", "Free-fall when situation unresolved, liquidity crisis, or litigation needed", "RSA / lock-up locks in creditor support before filing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These three sit on a spectrum of how much you negotiate before you ever file. In a pre-pack, you solicit votes and have an accepted plan in hand before the petition, so you file and emerge in weeks - it is fast, cheap, and minimizes business disruption, but it only works when the deal is consensual and the capital structure is clean enough to bind everyone quickly. A pre-arranged case is the middle ground: you sign a restructuring support agreement with your key creditors so the economic deal is locked, but you actually solicit votes inside the case, which buys you time to deal with classes you could not pre-solicit. A free-fall is filing with no agreed plan - you go in to get the automatic stay and breathing room, then negotiate the plan in court. You optimize a pre-pack for speed and cost, a pre-arranged for a balance of certainty and flexibility, and a free-fall for situations where liquidity is gone, litigation is unresolved, or you simply cannot get a deal done beforehand.$x$),
(1894, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Amend And Extend$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A borrower facing a 2028 maturity wall wants to do an amend-and-extend with its term loan lenders. Walk me through what an A and E is, what the lenders typically demand in return, and why a borrower might prefer it over a full refinancing.$x$, $x$["A&E pushes out maturity without replacing whole facility", "Lenders demand higher spread / margin bump and upfront fee", "Often amortization, covenant tightening, or additional security", "Avoids repricing entire capital structure at market", "Buys runway past refi wall without triggering full syndication", "Non-extending lenders can stay on old terms / maturity", "Cheaper and faster than new-money refinancing in tough market"]$x$::jsonb, $x$An amend-and-extend is exactly what it sounds like - you amend the existing credit agreement to push the maturity out, rather than refinancing the whole facility with brand new debt. It is attractive when there is a maturity wall coming, say 2028, and the borrower would rather not test the full market. In exchange for extending, lenders almost always demand a price - a higher spread, an upfront amendment or consent fee, and often some structural protection like added amortization, tighter covenants, or incremental collateral. Lenders who do not want to extend can usually stay on the original maturity and terms, so you can end up with two tranches. A borrower prefers this over a full refinancing because it is faster and cheaper, it does not require repricing the entire structure at current all-in rates, and in a higher-for-longer environment with a crowded refi wall, it avoids the risk that a fresh syndication prices wide or fails. The cost is that you are paying up and tightening the documents, and you have only deferred the problem, not solved it.$x$),
(1895, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Coercive Exchange Mechanics$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain what makes a distressed exchange coercive. What specific levers does an issuer use to push bondholders to tender, and what is the holdout problem you are trying to solve?$x$, $x$["Coercion: make not tendering worse than tendering", "Exit consents strip covenants / protections from old bonds", "Subordinate or prime non-tendering holders structurally", "New paper often senior, secured, or shorter-dated", "Holdout problem: free-ride on others haircut, keep full claim", "Threat of bankruptcy as the worse alternative", "Minimum participation / backstop conditions to bind class"]$x$::jsonb, $x$An exchange is coercive when the issuer engineers the deal so that staying out is worse than tendering, not because the new paper is generous. The classic lever is exit consents - holders who tender also vote to strip covenants and protections out of the old indenture, so anyone who holds out is left with a stub bond that has no covenant package and trades worse. The other big lever is priority: the new instrument is typically senior, secured, or structurally ahead, so non-tendering holders get effectively subordinated or primed and sit behind the people who participated. You are trying to solve the holdout problem - because changing core payment terms usually needs unanimous consent, a rational holdout would refuse the haircut, keep its full claim, and free-ride on everyone else who took the cut. Coercion plus a credible threat that the alternative is a messier, lower-recovery bankruptcy is what pushes participation over the minimum threshold. It is aggressive, and it is exactly why these deals draw litigation.$x$),
(1896, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Rights Offering Backstop$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A plan of reorganization is funded in part by a 300 million dollar rights offering with a backstop. Explain how the rights offering and backstop work, why the backstop parties get a fee, and what an analyst should watch for in terms of value transfer to insiders.$x$, $x$["Rights offering lets creditors buy new equity pro rata", "Usually priced at discount to plan equity value", "Backstop parties commit to buy unsubscribed shares", "Backstop / commitment fee paid in cash or discounted equity", "Ensures plan is fully funded / certainty of capital", "Watch for value leakage to ad hoc group / insiders", "Discount plus fee can be a disguised recovery enhancement"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A rights offering raises new money for the emerged company by giving existing creditors the right to buy new equity, usually pro rata to their claims and usually at a discount to the plan equity value, which is the incentive to participate. The backstop is an agreement by a group of large creditors - often the ad hoc group - to purchase any shares that other creditors do not subscribe, so the company is guaranteed to raise the full 300 million regardless of take-up. For taking that commitment risk, the backstop parties get a backstop or commitment fee, typically several percent, paid in cash or, more commonly, in additional discounted equity. What an analyst should watch closely is value transfer: between the subscription discount and the backstop fee, the backstoppers can capture meaningful upside that effectively enhances their recovery beyond what their claim alone would justify. Other creditors and the court scrutinize whether the discount and fee are market or whether they are a disguised payoff to insiders who controlled the process, which is a frequent objection point.$x$),
(1897, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Exit Financing$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What is exit financing in a Chapter 11, how does it differ from DIP financing, and why does arranging credible exit financing matter for whether a plan can actually be confirmed?$x$, $x$["Exit financing funds company as it leaves bankruptcy", "Replaces / takes out the DIP on emergence", "DIP is interim, super-priority, court-supervised", "Exit is the permanent post-emergence capital structure", "Feasibility requirement: plan must not be likely to re-file", "Often DIP-to-exit conversion to reduce execution risk", "Provides liquidity, funds plan distributions, working capital"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Exit financing is the capital the company lines up to fund itself on the way out of bankruptcy - it is the permanent post-emergence structure, often a new term loan and revolver, that provides liquidity, funds cash distributions under the plan, and supports working capital going forward. The key contrast with DIP financing is timing and role: a DIP is interim, super-priority, court-supervised money that keeps the lights on during the case, whereas exit financing is the takeout that repays or replaces the DIP when the company emerges. They are frequently linked - you will see DIP-to-exit conversion features where the same lenders roll their DIP into the exit facility to reduce execution risk and avoid re-syndicating in the market. Why it matters for confirmation is feasibility: the court has to find the plan is not likely to be followed by another filing, and a plan that emerges with no committed financing and a hole in liquidity fails that test. Credible, committed exit financing is what lets the judge and creditors believe the reorganized company can actually stand on its own.$x$),
(1898, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Debt For Equity Conversion$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$The fulcrum creditors are going to equitize their debt into the reorganized company. Walk me through the mechanics and the key judgment calls - how you size their ownership, what happens to old equity, and the trade-offs of taking equity versus a new debt instrument.$x$, $x$["Equitization: cancel claims, issue new equity to fulcrum", "Ownership sized off plan / reorg equity value and claim size", "Old equity typically wiped or heavily diluted per APR", "Reduces leverage, improves feasibility and go-forward liquidity", "Equity is upside / illiquid / no fixed return versus debt", "Negotiation over reorg value drives the split", "Management incentive plan and warrants for out-of-money classes"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Equitizing means the fulcrum creditors give up their claims and instead receive the new equity of the reorganized company, which deleverages the balance sheet in one move and is often what makes the plan feasible. Mechanically, the old claims are cancelled and new shares are issued, and you size each group's ownership off two things - the negotiated reorganization equity value and the size and priority of their claims. The fight is almost always over that reorg value, because a lower value lets the fulcrum take more of the equity while a higher value leaves room for junior classes. Old equity sits at the bottom of the waterfall, so under absolute priority it is typically wiped out or left with token warrants if senior classes consent to a gift. The trade-off for the creditor is risk versus return: equity gives you upside but it is illiquid, has no coupon, and sits last in line, whereas new debt gives you a contractual return and seniority but caps recovery. You also usually carve out a management incentive plan and sometimes warrants to keep out-of-the-money classes from blocking the plan.$x$),
(1899, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$DIP Roll-Up Priming$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$Explain how a DIP roll-up and a priming DIP work, why existing secured lenders often consent to being primed, and what adequate protection they are entitled to. Why are roll-ups controversial?$x$, $x$["Roll-up: pre-petition debt converted into super-priority DIP", "Priming DIP: new lien jumps ahead of existing secured liens", "Section 364(d) allows priming with consent or adequate protection", "Existing lenders often consent as defensive DIP to control case", "Adequate protection: replacement liens, cash payments, equity cushion", "Roll-up controversial: improves pre-petition recovery, elevates priority", "Ratio of new money to rolled-up debt is key scrutiny point"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A priming DIP is new financing whose lien jumps ahead of existing secured lenders' liens on the same collateral, which the code permits either with those lenders' consent or, over objection, only if they receive adequate protection. A roll-up goes further - it converts a lender's pre-petition claim into part of the super-priority DIP, so old debt gets elevated to the front of the line dollar for dollar with the new money. Existing secured lenders frequently consent, and often provide the DIP themselves, as a defensive move - as the DIP lender they control the budget and milestones and steer the case rather than let an outsider prime them. When primed without consent, they get adequate protection: replacement liens, periodic cash payments, or reliance on an equity cushion, all meant to guard against diminution in their collateral value. Roll-ups are controversial because they lift a pre-petition lender's recovery and priority with no new money behind the rolled portion, so courts scrutinize the ratio of new money to rolled debt - a one-to-one roll-up draws far more objection than two dollars of new money per dollar rolled.$x$),
(1900, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Advisor Side Conflicts$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$In a restructuring, what is the difference between advising the company versus advising an ad hoc group of creditors, and where do the conflicts and incentives diverge between those two mandates?$x$, $x$["Company-side banker works for board/management, maximizes enterprise outcome and runway", "Creditor-side advises ad hoc group, maximizes that class recovery and leverage", "Company runs the process/DIP/sale; creditors negotiate plan terms and scrutinize collateral", "Conflict: management wants equity/jobs, creditors want the keys or full recovery", "Inter-creditor friction - senior vs junior, net-long vs net-short holders", "Fiduciary/confidentiality and who pays the fees (company often funds both)"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Working for the company means I report to the board or a special committee, and my job is to maximize the overall outcome - extend runway, run the marketing or DIP process, and land a plan that keeps the enterprise alive, ideally leaving something for existing equity or management. Working for an ad hoc creditor group flips the goal: I am maximizing that specific class's recovery and negotiating leverage, scrutinizing collateral, liens, and the company's projections rather than building them. The deep conflict is that management naturally wants to preserve equity and jobs, while creditors often want the keys - convert debt to equity or force a sale. There is also inter-creditor friction: seniors and juniors fight over where value breaks, and net-short holders may not even want a deal. One quirk worth flagging is that the company usually funds the creditor advisors too, so fee disputes and good-faith negotiation get policed by the court. So same restructuring, opposite seats, opposite incentives.$x$),
(1901, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$RX Fee Structures$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Walk me through how a restructuring advisory mandate is typically compensated - the monthly fee, the completion or restructuring fee, and how crediting works - and why this fee structure looks so different from a standard M&A engagement.$x$, $x$["Monthly retainer fee - pays for long, uncertain timeline", "Completion/restructuring/transaction fee - large back-end success fee", "Fee often sized off face value of liabilities restructured, not equity value", "Crediting - monthlies partially offset against the back-end fee", "RX deals drag on or may die, so monthlies de-risk the bank", "Court approval of fees in Chapter 11 (retention and fee applications)"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A restructuring mandate usually has three pieces. First is a monthly retainer - a fixed fee, often a few hundred thousand dollars a month, that compensates the bank for a long, uncertain process that might never close. Second is the back-end: a completion fee, sometimes called a restructuring or transaction fee, which is the big number and is typically sized off the face value of the liabilities being restructured rather than off equity value, because in a distressed situation equity value may be near zero. Third is crediting - the monthlies you have already collected get partially credited against that back-end fee, so they reduce double-counting. This looks different from M&A because an M&A success fee is a percentage of deal equity value and the deal usually either closes in months or dies cleanly. Restructurings drag on, can pivot from out-of-court to in-court, and may collapse, so monthlies de-risk the engagement. And in Chapter 11 the fees are not purely private - the court reviews retention and fee applications, so the structure has to be defensible.$x$),
(1902, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Battle Of Experts$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$In a contested Chapter 11, junior creditors argue the enterprise is worth far more than the senior creditors claim. As an expert advising on valuation, explain why these disputes happen, what the parties are really fighting over, and the main levers each side pushes to move where value breaks.$x$, $x$["Value dispute = fight over where the fulcrum breaks / who is in-the-money", "Juniors want high TEV to reach their class; seniors want low TEV", "Levers: projections / exit multiple / WACC / normalized EBITDA add-backs", "DCF vs comparables vs precedent - dueling methodologies and weightings", "Case-specific risk, market window, control vs minority assumptions", "Judge picks a number or range; outcome drives recoveries and cramdown"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These fights happen because valuation in bankruptcy is not academic - it directly decides who is in-the-money and who gets wiped. The total enterprise value sets where the fulcrum breaks: if value comes in low, the seniors own the company and juniors recover little; if it comes in high, value spills past the seniors and the juniors, even equity, reach recovery. So each side hires experts who build to their answer. Juniors push for a high TEV: aggressive projections, a higher exit multiple, a lower discount rate, and add-backs that inflate normalized EBITDA. Seniors do the opposite - haircut the plan, use a lower multiple and higher WACC, and stress execution and market risk. They also fight over methodology weighting, DCF versus comps versus precedent deals, and control assumptions. Because the inputs are judgment calls, reasonable experts land far apart. Ultimately the judge picks a number or range at the valuation hearing, and that drives recoveries and whether the plan can be crammed down. It is a real battle of experts because recovery dollars hinge on a single multiple turn or a couple points of discount rate.$x$),
(1904, NULL, 'primary', $x$Restructuring$x$, $x$Net-Short Activism$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Explain net-short debt activism and the idea of a manufactured or engineered default. How can a creditor who is net short through CDS profit from pushing a borrower into default, and why does this distort a normal restructuring negotiation?$x$, $x$["CDS pays out on a credit event; net-short holder gains if the name defaults", "Net-short investor holds more CDS protection than underlying bonds/loans", "Manufactured/engineered default - induce a credit event, e.g. pay-to-delay or forced missed payment", "Misaligned holder wants default, not a consensual fix - breaks usual incentives", "Determinations Committee / failure-to-pay mechanics drive the CDS trigger", "Responses: net-short provisions, disqualifying votes, legal pushback (Hovnanian-style)"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Normally a creditor wants the borrower to survive so the debt gets repaid. A net-short investor flips that. They hold more credit default swap protection than they hold actual bonds or loans, so on a net basis they make money if the name defaults, because CDS pays out on a credit event. That creates an incentive to push the borrower into trouble rather than fix it. A manufactured or engineered default is exactly that: structuring a transaction to trigger a credit event. The classic example is paying a company to intentionally miss a small payment so a failure-to-pay event is declared, which the CDS Determinations Committee confirms, paying the protection buyer. In a restructuring this is corrosive because the usual logic - everyone wants a consensual deal that maximizes value - breaks down. A net-short holder may vote against any sensible fix, block an exchange, or even prefer a messier bankruptcy. The market responded with net-short provisions that strip voting rights from disqualified lenders, after cases like Hovnanian made the tactic notorious. So always ask whether a loud holdout is actually long the credit or quietly short it.$x$);
